## How Packs Load

`PromptTemplateRegistry.Load()` scans the config folder for all `.airpac` files at startup:

```csharp
var files = Directory.GetFiles(folderPath, "*.airpac", SearchOption.TopDirectoryOnly);
```

Multiple packs can coexist. Each pack adds its templates to the registry. The Letter Type dropdown shows all available `Title > MainType` combinations across all loaded packs. A fully loaded Airlock could simultaneously offer Legal, HR, Medical, and Property Management workflows from separate `.airpac` files — all in one dropdown.

---

## Import System

New packs are imported via the Import Templates tab (USB or local folder). The `_sigil` field is validated on import — only packs with the correct sigil are accepted. This is the trust boundary for the ecosystem.

```
USB drive → /mnt/AIBUSB/import/
    ↓
ImportTab scans for *.airpac
    ↓
Validates _sigil
    ↓
Copies to ~/Documents/AIBDOCS/config/
    ↓
Available on next app launch
```

---

## The Platform Implication

The friction to create a new vertical is:

1. Write a JSON file following the `.airpac` schema
2. Fill in the fields for your domain
3. Copy to the config folder
4. Relaunch Airlock

No code changes. No recompile. No deployment.

This means domain experts — lawyers, HR consultants, property managers, medical billers — can build their own workflow packs without touching the application. The schema is the SDK. If you can edit JSON, you can build an Airpack.

That is the platform model. Airlock is the runtime. Airpacks are the product layer. The two can evolve independently.

---

## Naming

The file extension is `.airpac` (not `.aibcodex` — that was the internal development name).

Pack files should be named descriptively:

```
legal_letters.airpac
hr_workflows.airpac
property_management.airpac
medical_appeals.airpac
```

Multiple packs can be installed simultaneously. The runtime merges them all into the dropdown at load time.

